Filtering network traffic is critical for securing Azure environments.

For example, an organization may allow only HTTPS traffic (port 443) to its web servers while blocking all other ports.

A real-life use case is protecting backend databases by allowing access only from application servers.

Another example is restricting administrative access (SSH/RDP) to specific IP addresses.

Companies also use Azure Firewall to block malicious traffic and enforce policies.

These practices help prevent unauthorized access and enhance overall security.
